Visual Observation Experiment of Natural Light Grid Arrangement

I. Experimental Purpose

To verify that light does not propagate in wave form, but is essentially a material ensemble composed of micro-units arranged in a regular, uniform grid;

To challenge the one-sided interpretation of moiré patterns by wave theory using everyday visible textures, proving that the core cause of optical fringes is grid misalignment rather than wave interference or superposition.

II. Experimental Equipment

Smartphone, computer/smartphone screen displaying pure white, ambient diffused indoor lighting, with no additional optical accessories.

III. Experimental Procedure

Set the electronic screen to a full-screen pure white display, ensuring uniform brightness of the emitting surface without any patterns or color patches.

First observation method:​ Observe the screen surface directly with the naked eye at an oblique angle, statically observing visual textures.

Second observation method:​ Use a smartphone camera aimed obliquely at the pure white screen, adjusting the shooting distance and zoom level slightly for photographic observation.

Repeat observations from multiple angles and distances, recording the patterns, density, direction, and variation rules of the textures.

IV. Experimental Observations

When observing the pure white screen obliquely with the naked eye, continuous, regular, fine alternating light and dark patterns are directly visible.

Periodic grid-like stripes (commonly defined as moiré patterns) also appear in images captured by the camera.

The density and orientation of the patterns change with the observation angle and distance, exhibiting uniform arrangement and stable periodicity overall.

V. Comparison with Mainstream Theoretical Explanations

Classical wave theory provides a fixed explanation for such patterns:

It claims that moiré patterns are merely imaging artifacts resulting from the overlap of two artificial arrays—the screen pixel grid and the camera sensor grid. This is considered a sampling error of the device, unrelated to the microstructure of light itself, and denies the existence of an intrinsic grid-like form of light.

VI. Experimental Analysis and Conclusion

In this experiment, patterns are visible through direct naked-eye observation without instruments. Since the human eye lacks a pixel sampling grid, this directly refutes the one-sided wave theory explanation that relies solely on device superposition.

The true cause of the phenomenon: Light inherently possesses a natural microscopic grid-like structure, and all solid material surfaces have intrinsic lattice arrangements.

When the intrinsic grid of light and the lattice grid on a material surface misalign or mismatch in spacing, visible light and dark stripes naturally appear.

In conclusion, moiré patterns are not electronic interference or imaging flaws but direct macroscopic evidence of the microscopic grid structure of light.

All optical diffraction and light-dark fringe phenomena share the same underlying principle: grid misalignment, gap occlusion, and path obstruction. There is no wave cancellation, wave superposition, or other virtual interactions.
